\begin_layout Enumerate
Since the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is decreasing on the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[1,\infty)$
\end_inset

,
 the upper Riemann sum is the same as the left Riemann sum,
 which in this case is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=f(x_{0})(x_{1}-x_{0})+f(x_{1})(x_{1}-x_{0})+\dots+f(x_{n-1})(x_{n}-x_{n-1}).
\]

\end_inset

Now,
 all the terms in this sum are positive,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $U\geq f(x_{n-1})(x_{n}-x_{n-1})$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x_{n-1})$
\end_inset

 is a positive number (because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n-1}<\infty$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}-x_{n-1}=\infty-x_{n-1}=\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\geq f(x_{n-1})\cdot\infty=\infty,
\]

\end_inset

and so we conclude 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

