 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{1}^{2^{n}}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x & =\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\int_{2}^{4}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\int_{4}^{8}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\dots+\int_{2^{n-1}}^{2^{n}}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x\\
 & =\underbrace{\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x+\dots+\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x}_{n}\\
 & =n\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is the conclusion we desired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the region between the graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/x$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 axis,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This region is clearly contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 and so its area is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 This area is given by the obvious integral,
 and so we conclude
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{1}^{2^{n}}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x\leq C.
\]

\end_inset

As a consequence,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C\geq n\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x$
\end_inset

 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by Item 
