reference "enu:pt2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 and thus,
 taking 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

,
 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $C\geq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 (This uses the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{1}^{2}\frac{1}{x}\,\dl x$
\end_inset

 is a positive number,
 but this is an obvious fact by looking at the picture.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The main issue with the proof is the very last step,
 where we subtract 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from both sides of 
\begin_inset Formula $A+1=A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A=C=\infty$
\end_inset

,
 subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\infty$
\end_inset

 from both sides leads to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty-\infty$
\end_inset

 indetermination.
 More generally,
 manipulating infinities like they were numbers is tricky business and needs to be done very carefully.
\end_layout

